{\fs20 Many motor skills require a person to perform with both speed and accuracy. For example, kicking a penalty kick in soccer, pitching a fastball for a \u173 ?
strike\u8239 ?in baseball and softball, playing a song on \u173 ?a\u8239 ?piano\u8239 ?at a fast tempo, and speed typing all require fast\u8239 ?
and accurate movement to achieve successful performance. For these skills, the speed and accuracy demands are determined by the skill itself. Other motor skills require limb-movement accuracy but not speed. For example, many }
{\*\cs57\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw0 manual aiming skills}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 ,}{\fs20  which involve hand movement to a target, require that the hand arrive at the target but at a speed that the performer determines. Such skills include putting a key into a keyhole, placing a pen in a penholder, typing on a computer keyboard, and threading a needle.\par }
\pard\plain \s12\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 For both types of speed-accuracy skills, those that require fast and accurate movement and those that require accurate movement at an unspecified speed, we commonly observe a phenomenon known as the }
{\*\cs57\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw0 speed-accuracy trade-off}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 .}{\fs20  This means that the accuracy requirements of the movement will \u173 ?
influence the movement speed so that an emphasis on accuracy will reduce speed, while an emphasis on speed will reduce accuracy. Thus, we typically \ldblquote trade of}
{\fs20 f}{\fs20 \rdblquote  speed for accuracy, and vice versa. Consider how this trade-off would occur in the \u173 ?examples of the two types of skills described above. For a penalty kick in soccer, when a player tries to kick the\u8239 ?
ball at the fastest speed possible, the typical \u173 ?result is an inaccurate kick. Conversely, when the player emphasizes accuracy by trying to kick the ball to a small part of the goal, the result is often a ball kicked too slowly to get past the goalkeeper. For the\u8239 ?
example of putting a key in a keyhole, moving the key too quickly toward the keyhole typically \u173 ?results in}{\fs20\u8239 ?missing the keyhole, whereas an emphasis on \u173 ?
accuracy results in slower hand movement.\par }\pard\plain \s13\f4\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb270\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
