{\fs20 & }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 Chua, 2001, for a review of Woodworth\rquote s experiments and influence on research). For the following half century, evidence for a speed-accuracy trade-off in motor skill performance had become so common that a mathematical law was developed to predict movement speed given specific accuracy characteristics. This law, which has become known as Fitts\rquote  law, was described by and based on the work of Paul Fitts (1954). It has become one of the\u8239 ?
most significant \ldblquote laws\rdblquote  associated with human performance. In science, a }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw2
law}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2  refers to a situation in which a result, or outcome, can be predicted when certain variables are involved.\par }
