{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 \par }\pard\plain \s17\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb260\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs59\f6\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd0\expndtw-1\cf0\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 Open- and closed-loop motor control processes related to the speed-\u173 ?
accuracy trade-off.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 \u8194\'20Researchers have proposed several hypotheses to explain the motor control processes related to the speed-\line accuracy trade-off. Most have elaborated on \u173 ?}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 Woodworth\rquote s (1899) original hypothesis, which }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 was that two motor control processes operate during the rapid limb movement to a target. One, which occurs initially and moves the limb into the vicinity of the target, is an }
{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0 open-loop control}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0  process where the initial movement}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0
\rquote s speed, direction, and accuracy are under CNS \u173 ?control without feedback. The second process involves }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0
closed-loop \u173 ?control}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0  in which visual feedback about the limb\rquote s relative position to that target is used to guide the \ldblquote homing in\rdblquote  phase of the limb to ensure its accurate landing on the target. The hypotheses proposed since Woodworth\rquote s have focused on providing more detailed descriptions of the motor control activities involved in either the open}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 - or closed-loop, or both, phases of the movement. However, all agree that, as\u8239 ?we discussed in chapter 6, the amount of\u8239 ?
time available is the primary determinant of whether a person can make movement corrections as the limb nears the target. This means that if the movement speed is too fast during the initial open-loop phase, there will not be sufficient time for \u173 ?
visual feedback to generate a movement adjustment as the limb nears the target.\par }\pard\plain \s17\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb258\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs59\f6\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd0\expndtw2\cf0\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 The role of visual information in the speed-\u173 ?
accuracy trade-off.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 \u8194\'20When we consider the in\u8209 ?\line volvement of our sensory-perceptual systems in the performance of a speed-accuracy skill, such as putting a key into a keyhole, vision plays a predominant role in enabling successful performance. }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 However, it is worth noting that blind individuals have also shown the influence of Fitts}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2
\rquote }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2  law, as demonstrated in the study by El Lahib and colleagues (2018) in which a vibrating touch screen was used for blind participants to tap specific shapes on the screen. }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 \par }\pard\plain \s12\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 The specific role played by vision in speed-accuracy skills depends on the phase of the limb movement. Although the hypotheses described in the preceding section proposed two distinct movement phases for these skills, an open-loop and a closed-loop phase, researchers generally agree that including a third phase is important to \u173 ?
understand the role of vision in the control }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 process}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 . This additional phase involves the preparation \line of the movements required to perform the skill. }
{\fs20 Figure 7.2 illustrates the relationship of this phase to the two movement phases for performing the manual aiming skill of putting a key into a keyhole, which is an example of a skill in which the speed-accuracy trade-off occurs.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 \par }{\fs20 The }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i first phase}{\fs20  is the }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i movement preparation phase, }
{\fs20 which begins when the person makes the decision to perform the skill involving a speed-\u173 ?accuracy trade-off. In this phase, the person uses vision to determine the regulatory conditions that characterize the environmental context in which the action will occur. For example, for the action of putting a key into a keyhole, the regulatory conditions would include the size, shape, and weight of the key and the size, location, and spatial orientation of the keyhole. These characteristics would specify the direction and distance of the limb movement as well as the accuracy demands of the situation. Together with other relevant information detected by the sensory system, such as the characteristics of the key that touch would provide, this sensory information would be transmitted to the CNS to prepare the specific movement characteristics to initiate and carry out the intended action. \par }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-5 Included in the movement preparation phase is the }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 selection of a speed- or accuracy-based strategy to }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-5 perform the skill. Recent fMRI evidence shows that the strategy selected activates different brain regions }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-5 \line }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-5 (Val}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 lesi, McIntosh, Crescentini, & Stuss, 2012). This evi}
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-5 dence provides an interesting level of support for the }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-5 behavioral trade-off observed as different brain regions }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 are involved in the preparation of the movement.}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 \par }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3
The }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i second phase}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3  is commonly referred to as the }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i initial flight phase.}
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3  It includes the beginning of the limb movement in the direction of the target, which }{\fs20 in our example is the keyhole. As you read in the preceding section, this movement is relatively fast \line (i.e., ballistic) and occurs without the influence of }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 sensory feedback. Although vision plays a \u173 ?minor role \line }{\fs20 in this phase, it acquires limb displacement and velocity information and acquires time-to-contact information that will be used later as the movement nears the target to make movement modifications. Researchers continue to debate the need }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 for\u8239 ?vision of the moving limb during this phase \line }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 (see Elliott, Helsen, }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 & Chua, 2001, for a discussion of the research concerning this\'caissue).\par }\pard\plain \s12\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 The third phase is the }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-4 termination phase.}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4
 It begins just before and ends when the target is hit, which in our example is when the key is inserted into the keyhole. Vision of the limb and target are important in this phase so that movement accuracy information can be transmitted to the CNS and any needed movement corrections can occur to allow the person to achieve the action goal of hitting the target.\par }
\pard\plain \s12\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 One final point to consider here is the way in }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 which }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-4
vision and movement interact}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4  in skills involv}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 ing a speed-accuracy trade-off. Note that the intended }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 action influences the way in which vision functions. }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 In the three phases of the manual aiming task just }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 discussed, the intent to put a key in a keyhole directs vision to focus on the keyhole itself, which provides during the movement preparation phase the critical regulatory conditions to which the movements will need to conform. Visual information during this phase also establishes the basis for the initial movement trajectory and velocity for moving the key toward the keyhole. During the termination phase, the action goal to put the key into the keyhole directs vision to detect speed and accuracy information that will allow precise movement adjustments to achieve the action goal.\par }
\pard\plain \s18\f4\fs21\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb360\sa120\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\keepn\caps\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs21 Prehension\par }\pard\plain \s11\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs57\fs20\b\i0\expnd-1\expndtw-4 Prehension}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4  is the general term used to describe \u173 ?actions involving the }
{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-4 reaching for and grasping of objects.}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4  Research evidence has shown that the movements involved in prehension consist of three distinct components: }
{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-4 transport, grasp,}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4  and }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-4 object }
{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-3 manipulation.}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3  The object manipulation component refers to the functional goal for the prehension action. This means that an important part of understanding the control of \u173 ?
prehension\'d1unlike pointing and aiming \u173 ?movements\'d1relates to what the person intends to do with the object after grasping it. The importance of this component is that it influences the kinematic and kinetic characteristics of the transport and grasp components. For example, if a person intends to pick up a cup to drink from it, the transport and grasp characteristics will differ from those associated with the person picking up the cup and moving it to a different location on a table (see Newell & Cesari, 1999, for a discussion of the motor control implications of this issue). In fact, it is because of the relationship of the object manipulation component to the other two components that prehension must be considered an action that is different from the action of reaching and pointing to an object.}
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 \par }\pard\plain \s13\f4\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb280\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 The Relationship between Prehension Components\par }\pard\plain \s11\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw3 From a motor control perspective, prehension involves the arm transporting the hand to an object as\u8239 ?
the hand forms the grip characteristics that are\u8239 ?needed to grasp the object. A motor control \u173 ?question of interest here concerns the relationship \u173 ?
between the }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd1\expndtw3 transport and grasp components.}{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw3  \u173 ?Although initial attempts to answer this question proposed that these components were relatively \u173 ?
independent (e.g., Jeannerod, 1981, 1984), more \u173 ?recent evidence has established that these }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd1\expndtw3
two \u173 ?components are temporally coupled and interact synergistically}{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw3  (i.e., cooperatively) according to task demands. This means that although the reach and the grasp are two separate movement components, they function in an interdependent manner.}
{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw3 \par }\pard\plain \s12\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 The most compelling evidence demonstrating this\u8239 ?coupled relationship has come from movement analyses of the fingers and thumb as the hand moves\u8239 ?
toward the object. For example, }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 in their highly influential research}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  Jakobson and\u8239 ?
Goodale (1991) showed that the object\rquote s size and\u8239 ?distance from the hand influenced the timing of when the distance between the fingers and thumb (i.e., grip aperture) reaches its maximum during the transport component }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 of the reach}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 . Interestingly, they, along with others (e.g., Chieffi & Gentilucci, 1993; Hu, Osu, Okada, Goodale, & Kawato, 2005}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 ; Volcic & Domini, 2016}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 ), found that }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 regardless of object size and distance, maximum grip aperture and hand closure occurred at \u173 ?
approximately two-thirds of the total movement time duration}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  of the action. More conclusive support for the temporal coupling of hand transport and grip aperture was provided by researchers who presented a mathematical model that can predict this temporal relationship for any hand transport duration (Hu et al., 2005). As is consistent with the research just described, this model shows that the maximum grip aperture occurs when the hand is approximately two-thirds through the total time duration of the reaching movement.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 \par }\pard\plain \s12\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 In addition, research evidence has shown that the kinematics of both the transport and grasp components are modified when the object is suddenly and unexpectedly moved during the transport phase (e.g.,\u8239 ?
Gentilucci, Chieffi, Scarpa, & Castiello, 1992), and when an obstacle needs to be avoided to\u8239 ?get to the\u8239 ?object (e.g., Saling, Alberts, Stelmach, & Bloedel, }
{\fs20 1998). These kinematic changes give additional }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 support to the conclusion that there is a strong }
{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i temporal coupling }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 between the reach and grasp components of a prehension action. Thus, prehension serves as an additional example to those described in chapter 5 \line of how muscles and joints involved in a complex action cooperate synergistically as a }
{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i coordinative structure}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3  to enable people to achieve an action goal in a variety of situations.}
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 \par }\pard\plain \s13\f4\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb260\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 The Role of Vision in Prehension\par }\pard\plain \s11\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 Prehension actions are a type of speed-accuracy skill because accurate hand movement is required and the movement speed will be influenced by that accuracy demand. As a result, we should expect to find that vision is involved in prehension actions in ways that are similar to those we discussed in the preceding section on speed-\u173 ?
accuracy skills. In fact, this is the case, with one \u173 ?exception. The exception involves the object manipulation component of prehension actions. \par }
\pard\plain \s12\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 Consistent with its role in the speed-\u173 ?accuracy skills we discussed previously, vision assists the planning of prehension \u173 ?
actions by providing information about the regulatory conditions of the environmental context. Together with the person\rquote s intended use of the object, the regulatory condition information is transmitted to the CNS, which then prepares \ldblquote ballpark}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \rdblquote  estimates of the spatial and temporal characteristics for the transport and grasp components of the reaching movement. Evidence for the importance of visual information about object properties in this CNS planning activity was provided in a study that required participants to reach and grasp a variety of different objects (Verhagen, Dijkerman, Medendorp, & Toni, 2012). \par }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2\u173 ?Vision next plays an essential role as the hand travels toward the object by detecting when the hand will contact the object so that the timing of the grip aperture can be controlled appropriately. It also provides information about the spatial characteristics of the grip relative to the object\rquote s size, shape, and orientation so that the spatial characteristics of the grip can be controlled appropriately. Visual feedback related to these movement characteristics will be used by the CNS to modify movements as needed to allow achievement of the prehension action goal. In fact, research has shown that grasp characteristics are negatively affected when a person cannot see the object during the initial portion of the transport phase (Fukui & Inui, 2006). Unlike the speed-\u173 ?
accuracy skills we discussed earlier, vision monitors the grasp itself to supplement tactile and proprioceptive feedback to ensure that the grasp adjusts as needed during the grasping and manipulation of the object. }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 And, as Volcic and Domini (2016) found, grasping movements are }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \ldblquote }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2
smoothly and automatically adjusted to the current visual feedback.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \'ca}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 .}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2
\'ca}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 .}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \rdblquote }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \line }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2
(p. 2174) even when it might be more advantageous to disregard the visual feedback and rely only on the haptic feedback. }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2
\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 As you read in chapter 6, binocular vision enhances the performance of \u173 ?prehension actions, especially in terms of the preparation of grip size and force (Jackson, Newport, & Shaw, 2002). In addition, research by Brown, Halpert, and \u173 ?
Goodale (2005) has shown that because of the different roles of central and peripheral vision, especially as they relate to the two visual systems of vision-for-perception and vision-for-action, prehension skill performance is enhanced when the person looks directly at the object. This directing of the point of gaze at the object allows the two visual systems to optimally function during the prehension action.}
{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-1 \par }\pard\plain \s13\f4\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb260\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Prehension and Fitts\rquote  Law\par }\pard\plain \s11\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 One final point that is important to note with regard to the motor control aspects of prehension is that it demonstrates speed-accuracy trade-off character\u173 ?
istics. In fact, researchers have established that Fitts\rquote  law consistently applies to prehension for both laboratory tasks and activities of daily living. For \u173 ?
example, in an experiment by Bootsma, Marteniuk, MacKenzie, \line and Zaal (1994), movement distance and object width influenced movement time during prehension in accordance with the predictions of Fitts}
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 \rquote  law. In addition, these object characteristics \u173 ?influenced the movement kinematics of the action. The relevance of the kinematic evidence is that it provides a way to explain why movement time increases as object width decreases. The kinematics showed that as objects decrease in size, the amount of time involved in the deceleration phase of the movement increases, suggesting that the increase in movement time associated with the smaller objects is due to the\u8239 ?
person reducing the speed of the limb as it approaches the object. This means that when a person reaches for a cup that has a small handle, not only will the transport and grasp kinematics differ from reaching for a cup with no handle, but the movement time will also be slower, because of the increased \u173 ?
accuracy demands of grasping the small handle.\par }\pard\plain \s12\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 A different approach to relating prehension actions to Fitts\rquote  law was reported by Latash and Jaric (2002). They developed a way to identify an index of difficulty that would account for the size of a mug and the amount of liquid in it. They reasoned that reaching, grasping, and drinking from a mug demands accuracy in a way that should influence arm movement speed as well as coordination of the limb segments involved, which means that Fitts\rquote  law should apply. But the accuracy component for this type of task is different from manual aiming tasks. Drinking from a mug, or any container, involves not only the size of the \u173 ?
container or handle, but also how full it is. This is \u173 ?because the movement involved is transporting the \u173 ?container from its location to the person\rquote s mouth without spilling the \u173 ?
contents. In their experiment, the researchers developed a ratio of mug size and water level that calculated an index of difficulty, which like Fitts}
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 \rquote  law predicted movement times from initial mug movement to the drinker\rquote s mouth.\par }\pard\plain \s13\f4\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Implications for Practice\par }\pard\plain \s11\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 From an applied perspective, the motor control \u173 ?research evidence about prehension has important \u173 ?
implications for the development of practice conditions to help people improve their prehension \u173 ?capabilities. Because of the cooperative relationship between the reach, grasp, and object manipulation components, it is essential that prehension practice or therapy strategies involve functional activities (e.g., Wu, Trombly, Lin, }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 & Tickle-Degnen, 1998}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 Winstein, Wulf, & Schweighofer, 2015}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 ). \u173 ?In\u8239 ?addition, because movement characteristics of reach and grasp components interact in \u173 ?
various ways according to object characteristics, it is important that practice involve reaching, grasping, and manipulating a variety of object characteristics and manipulation goals. Finally, because of the interdependent relationship of the components of prehension, it would not be beneficial to separate the reach, grasp, and object manipulation goal so that a person could practice each component separately. It is worth noting that researchers in Australia have incorporated these suggestions for developing a virtual reality system designed to improve reaching and grasping skills for traumatic brain}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 -}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 injured people. The system (called Elements) engages participants in a variety of movements to various shapes, sizes, and locations of virtual objects (Mumford}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 et al., 2012).\par }\pard\plain \s18\f4\fs21\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb320\sa120\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\keepn\caps\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs21 Handwriting\par }\pard\plain \s11\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 Investigation of the control mechanisms responsible for handwriting is a prominent theme in the\u8239 ?study of motor control (see Bullock, 2004). \u173 ?
Researchers generally agree that different control }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 mechanisms are involved in controlling }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i
what \u173 ?people write}{\fs20  (letters, words, numbers, etc.) and }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i how they write it}{\fs20  (the writing strokes producing the \u173 ?
letters, words, etc., on the writing surface).\par }\pard\plain \s12\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 When we consider the act of handwriting from an anatomical perspective, we see that there is a great deal of individual variation in terms of limb segment involvement. But when researchers obtain handwriting samples from one person, they offer strong evidence for what Bernstein (1967) referred }
{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw6 to as }{\*\cs57\fs20\b\i0\expnd1\expndtw6 motor equivalence}{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw6 .}{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw6
 That is, a person can }{\fs20 adapt to the specific demands of the writing \u173 ?context and adjust size, force, direction, and even muscle involvement to accommodate those demands. The notable outcome is that there is a great degree of similarity in characteristics such as letter forms, writing slant, relative force for stroke production, and relative timing between strokes. People have little trouble varying characteristics such as movement time and writing size, among others.\par }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 The complexity of handwriting control makes it difficult to develop a simple control model describing the components of this process. A person can write his or her signature or a familiar phrase with the preferred hand, with the nonpreferred hand, with a foot, or by holding a pen in the mouth. This suggests that at least the spatial features of writing are represented in the memory system in an abstract form. Also, this motor equivalence capability suggests the involvement of coordinative structures in handwriting control.\par }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-5 Another interesting feature of the act of handwrit}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 ing is that several control processes occur at the same time. To write a sentence, a person must use lexical and semantic cognitive processes, as well as\u8239 ?
motor control processes. Writing requires the \u173 ?person to \u173 ?retrieve words from memory. These words must have meanings that fit what the writer intends to convey. The written sentence requires specific grammatical construction. The words \u173 ?
require a certain spelling, which involves the person}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 \rquote s movement of the limb to produce specific \u173 ?
letters that are of an appropriate size and shape for what he or she is writing on. Further, the individual must hold the writing instrument with an appropriate amount of force to allow these letters to be formed. The capability of humans to carry out these various cognitive and motor \u173 ?
elements in relatively short amounts of time demonstrates both the complexity and the \u173 ?elegance of the control processes underlying the act of handwriting.\par }
\pard\plain \s13\f4\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Vision and Handwriting\par }\pard\plain \s11\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 A substantial amount of research evidence indicates that vision plays an important role in the \u173 ?control of handwriting actions. One of the best demonstrations of this role was provided by Smyth and Silvers (1987), who showed that a person who is asked to write with his or her eyes closed adds \u173 ?
extra strokes to some letters, omits strokes from some letters, and duplicates some letters. And if \u173 ?visual feedback is delayed while a person is writing, that person makes many errors, including \u173 ?
repeating and adding letters.}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 \par }\pard\plain \s12\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 On the basis of their own research and that of others, Smyth and Silvers proposed that vision performs two distinct functions in the control of handwriting. One function is to help the writer }
{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0 control the overall spatial arrangement of words on a horizontal line.}{\fs20  We see an example of this function in figure 7.3, where handwriting samples taken from people writing without vision available show distinct deviations from a horizontal line. The second function for vision is to help the writer }
{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0 produce \u173 ?accurate handwriting patterns,}{\fs20  such as the appropriate strokes and letters required for the written material. Again, evidence of this is seen in figure 7.3. People who wrote without vision available added or omitted strokes, added extra letters, deleted letters, and reversed letters.}
{\*\cs60\fs20\super 1}{\*\cs60\fs16\super 1}{\fs16 For a review and synthesis of research addressing the roles of various types of sensory feedback in handwriting, see Danna and Velay (2015).}
{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s18\f4\fs21\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb300\sa120\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\keepn\caps\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs21 Bimanual Coordination Skills\par }\pard\plain \s11\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 In addition to unimanual coordination skills, people perform many motor skills that require the simulta\u8209 ?
\line neous performance of the two arms, that is, }{\*\cs57\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-1 bimanual \line co\u8209 ?ordination}{\fs20
.}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3  Sometimes the two limbs do essentially the same thing (}{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i symmetric bimanual coordination}
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 ); this occurs when someone rows a boat or when a \u173 ?person in a wheelchair rolls the wheels of the chair in\u8239 ?
order to go straight forward or backward. But more\u8239 ?interesting from a motor control perspective are }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i asymmetric bimanual coordination}
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3  situations in which each limb must do something different. For example, a guitar player holds strings with one hand to determine chords, while plucking or striking strings }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 with the other hand to produce sound. A skilled drummer }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 can produce one rhythm with one hand while producing another with the other hand. The serve in tennis requires the player to toss the ball into the air with one arm while moving the racquet with a very different movement pattern with the other. And unscrewing the cap from a jar requires each hand to \u173 ?
perform different movements because one hand holds the jar.\par }\pard\plain \s13\f4\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb260\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Bimanual Coordination Preferences\par }\pard\plain \s11\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 An intriguing question about the performance of bimanual coordination skills is this: }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i Why is it more difficult to perform skills that require asymmetric than symmetric bimanual coordination?}
{\fs20  For example, why is it difficult to rub your stomach with one hand while at the same time tapping the top of your head with the other hand? This task is clearly more difficult to perform (especially the first time you try it) than doing the same movements with each hand. The answer to this question is based on an important characteristic of the motor control system: its inherent preference for controlling limb movements; it prefers symmetry. For the two arms, this means that the two limbs }
{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i prefer}{\fs20  }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 to do the same thing at the same time. This preference }{\fs20 helps the perfor\u8209 ?
\line mance of symmetric bimanual skills, but can lead to problems for asymmetric skills.\par }\pard\plain \s12\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1 The earliest research to demonstrate the motor control system\rquote s preference to coordinate the two arms to move together involved the simultaneous performance of discrete movements. In what is now seen as a classic series of experiments, Kelso, Southard, and Goodman (1979) had people perform rapid aiming movements simultaneously with each arm to targets that had the same or different Fitts\rquote  index of difficulty (ID) values}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1 . Results showed a }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0 temporal basis}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1  for the coordination of the two arms as they moved with similar movement times not only to two targets with the same ID values, but also to two targets that had different ID values.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1 \par }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 In the bimanual coordination task just described, the }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-4
more difficult }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 (according to the Fitts\rquote  law definition) }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 of the two aiming tasks \u173 ?
influenced the performance of the arm doing the less-difficult task. That is, the arm that was required to move a shorter distance (i.e., the less-difficult task) slowed down in comparison to when it moved the same distance alone. Similar results have been shown when }
{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-4 task complexity}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4  differences characterized the bimanual coordination task. For\u8239 ?
example, the task used in an experiment by Swinnen, Schmidt, Nicholson, and Shapiro (1990) \u173 ?required \u173 ?partici\u173 ?
pants\u8239 ?to rapidly move their arms in different spatial-temporal patterns. The task \u173 ?involved \u173 ?moving one arm in a simple one-\u173 ?
direction arm-\u173 ?flexion movement while at the same time moving the other in \u173 ?a\u8239 ?two-part flexion and extension movement. Both arms were to complete their movements in a \u173 ?
movement time of 800 msec. At the beginning of \u173 ?practice, participants generally produced with each arm the similar movement patterns, which \u173 ?
typically \u173 ?resembled the more complex two-part movement \u173 ?required by one arm.}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 \par }\pard\plain \s13\f4\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Motor Control of Bimanual Coordination\par }\pard\plain \s11\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 Researchers are not certain how bimanual co-\line ordination is controlled. At present, we know that the two arms are coupled into a coordinative structure that prefers \u173 ?
spatial-temporal symmetry. And an in-phase relationship between the arms (i.e., both arms flexing and \u173 ?then extending at the same time) appears to be the predominant symmetrical pattern. In addition, we know that with practice, a person can learn to \u173 ?
uncouple (sometimes referred to as \ldblquote dissociate}{\fs20 \rdblquote ) the two limbs and simultaneously move his or her arms asymmetrically. But, we do not yet understand the control mechanisms involved in this dissociation process. Some researchers (e.g., Verschueren et\u8239 ?
al., 1999a) report evidence that }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0 proprioceptive feedback }{\fs20 is important in this process, while others (e.g., Mechsner, Kerzel, \line }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 Knoblich, & Prinz, 2001) propose that }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw2 visual }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0
feedback}{\fs20  is the basis for performing the complex asymmetric bimanual coordination.}{\fs20  (See Shea, Buchanan, & Kennedy, 2016, for a more recent review of research related to this issue.)}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 \par }\pard\plain \s12\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 Motor control theories have inspired two distinct views on how people learn to uncouple their limbs. Those who support the motor program theory argue for generalized motor program involvement, but there is disagreement about whether two new generalized motor programs develop so that each arm becomes controlled by a separate program or whether one generalized motor program develops in which each arm can perform somewhat independently. From a dynamical systems theory perspective, the control issue is rather straightforward. The initial tendency for the arms to be spatially and temporally coupled represents an attractor state characterized by a specific relative phase relationship. But, with practice, the stable pattern is destabilized and a new attractor emerges as the new pattern becomes stabilized. (See Boyles, Panzer, & Shea, \line }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 2012}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 ;}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3  Oliveira & Ivry, 2008}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3
; and Shea, Buchanan, & }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 \line }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 Kennedy}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 , 2016,}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2
 for more in-depth discussions of the motor control of bimanual movements.)\par }\pard\plain \s13\f4\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb180\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Implications for Practice}{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s11\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 Teachers, coaches, and therapists who are aware of bimanual coordination tendencies will recognize the need to give special attention to people who are learning skills that require the arms to perform different spatial-temporal movement patterns. The required unlinking of bimanual movements can be a difficult process for people. But, as both experience and research evidence (e.g., Kovacs, Buchanan, & Shea, 2010; Lee, Swinnen, & Verschueren, 1995; Swinnen et al., 1990; Walter & Swinnen, 1994) tell us, people can achieve success in performing these types of skills when they receive appropriate \u173 ?
instruction, feedback, and practice. We will consider some of the strategies practitioners can use to\u8239 ?facilitate the learning of asymmetric bimanual coordination skills in Units V and VI.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \par }\pard\plain \s18\f4\fs21\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb320\sa120\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\keepn\caps\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs21 Catching a Moving Object\par }\pard\plain \s11\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 In many ways, catching an object is like the prehension action discussed earlier. However, there are two important differences. First, catching involves intercepting a moving object; prehension typically involves a stationary object. Second, the grasp of the object in the catching action ends the action; prehension typically involves doing something with the grasped object. Although in some sport situations, such as baseball and softball, there are occasions in which a player must remove the ball from the glove after the catch and throw the ball, this situation is uniquely sport and situation specific and will not be included in this \u173 ?
discussion of catching.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 \par }\pard\plain \s13\f4\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb200\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Three Phases of Catching an Object\par }\pard\plain \s11\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 To catch an object, the person must first move the arm and hand toward the oncoming object. Then, he or she must shape the hand to catch the object. \u173 ?
Finally, the fingers must grasp the object.\par }\pard\plain \s12\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 Williams and McCririe (1988) provided \u173 ?research}{\fs20  evidence demonstrating the phases of catching with their study of 11-year-old boys trying to catch a ball with one hand (}
{\fs20 figure 7.4). A movement analysis of the catching action showed the following sequence. }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 There was no arm motion for the first 160 to 240 msec }
{\fs20 of the ball flight. Then, elbow flexion gradually \u173 ?began and continued slowly and uniformly for about 80 percent of the ball flight. At about the same time, the fingers began to extend. The hand began to withdraw from the oncoming ball until about one-half of the ball flight time had elapsed. Then the upper arm accelerated about the shoulder, which resulted in the hand\rquote s being transported to the spatial position required for intercepting the ball. Boys who caught the ball began final positioning action 80 msec earlier than boys who failed to catch it. By the time 75 percent of the ball flight was complete (113 msec prior to contact), each successful boy had his hand and fingers in a ready state for catching the ball.}
{\fs20 \par }{\fs20 These results indicate that vision provides advance information enabling the motor control system to }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0
spatially and temporally set the arms, hands, and fingers before the ball arrives}{\fs20  so that the individual can catch the ball. It is especially noteworthy here that the person bases the grasping \u173 ?
action on visual information obtained }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0 before}{\fs20  the ball actually makes contact with the hand, rather than on feedback obtained after the ball has hit the hand. The extent of involvement of proprioception during pre\'d0ball contact stages is not well understood. However, we know that proprioceptive and tactile feedback become involved after contact because the catcher needs to make adjustments to the grasp. Research evidence also shows that both central and peripheral vision operate when a person picks up information critical to catching an object.}
{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s13\f4\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Vision of the Object and Catching\par }\pard\plain \s11\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw6 Catching an object, such as a ball, is a complex }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 perception-action skill that has challenged researchers in their efforts to understand how the visual and motor control systems interact. The results of these research efforts have identified several factors that influence successful catching which relate specifically to the visual observation of the object.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 \par }\pard\plain \s17\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb256\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs59\f6\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 Amount of visual contact time.}
{\fs20 \u8194\'20One factor is the amount of time of visual contact with the moving object. Research evidence indicates that constant visual contact is needed during two critical periods of time in the object\rquote s flight: the initial part of the flight and the period of time just prior to contact with the hand(s). How much time is required during each of these time periods has not been established, and undoubtedly depends on the situation. \par }
\pard\plain \s12\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 Some researchers have reported evidence indicating that observation of the initial flight should continue until the ball reaches its zenith (Amazeen, Amazeen, Post, & Beek, 1999), although others have indicated that only the first 300 msec of flight are important (e.g., Whiting, Gill, & Stephenson, 1970). The important point here is that visual contact with the object is needed for an amount of time during its initial flight phase that is sufficient to obtain information to determine estimates of the direction and distance of the flight. }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 (See Lopez-Molinar et al., 2010, for more recent evidence to support this point.)}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3
\par }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 In terms of visual contact with the object during its final portion of flight, research evidence indicates that the time period between 200 and 300 msec before hand contact is critical for successful catching (Savelsbergh, Whiting, Pijpers, & van Santvoord, 1993), although the precise amount of time may depend on the specific characteristics of the situation, especially the length of time the object is in flight and its velocity (see Bennett, Davids, & Craig, 1999). The need to see the ball during the final portion of its flight is to obtain specific time-to-contact information for the final spatial positioning of the hand and fingers, and the timing of the closing of the fingers during the grasp of the object.\par }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 What about visual contact with the object in flight between these two time periods? Research by Elliott and his colleagues (e.g., Elliott, Zuberec, & Milgram, 1994) indicates that continuous visual contact with the ball during this period of time is }
{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 not}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  essential. The Elliott et al. (1994) study showed that people can\u8239 ?
catch a ball that has a flight time of 1 sec by }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 intermittently seeing brief \ldblquote snapshots\rdblquote }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  (approximately 20 msec) of the ball every 80 msec of its flight. }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 Thus, people can use visual samples of ball flight characteristics to obtain the information they need to catch the ball. This capability to use intermittent visually detected information to catch an object helps us understand how an ice hockey goalie can catch a puck or a soccer goalkeeper can catch a ball even though he or she must visually track it through several pairs of legs on its way to the goal.\par }
\pard\plain \s17\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb200\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\f4\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-2 Tau}{\*\cs59\f6\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd0\expndtw-2\cf0\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0
 and catching.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \u8194\'20}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 Another important motor control question concerning vision of the object and catching is this: Does the motor control system use the visual variable }
{\f3\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 tau}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  to enable people to catch an object? Although there is considerable debate about the answer to this question (see Caljouw, van der Ramp, & Savelsbergh, 2004, for a more complete discussion of this issue), a significant amount of research evidence indicates that }
{\f3\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 tau}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  is involved in solving the time-to-contact problem when catching an object, although }
{\f3\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 tau}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  alone does not appear to be\u8239 ?sufficient to explain vision\rquote s role in catching (Mazyn, Lenoir, Montagne, & Savelsbergh, 2004).\par }
\pard\plain \s12\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 When an object moves directly toward a person, }{\fs20 the projected size of the object on the retina expands at a non-linear rate as the object approaches.}
{\fs20  }{\fs20 The object expands more slowly when the object is farther away but increases its rate of expansion as it gets closer}
{\fs20 . It is this rate of expansion }{\fs20 of angular size, which is often referred to as }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i looming}{\f3\fs20\b0\i
,}{\fs20  that the visual system uses to determine when collision of the object with the person will occur. For the action of catching, this optical \u173 ?
ex\u173 ?pansion establishes }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i when}{\fs20  the }{\fs20 movement must be initiated and how quickly it must be completed}
{\fs20  to catch the object. For objects that do not move directly toward the person but require the person to run to catch them, }
{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i tau}{\fs20  also provides the visual basis for timing the catch, although the mathematics for calculating }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i
tau}{\fs20  are distinctly more complex.\par }\pard\plain \s17\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb200\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs59\f6\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd0\expndtw-2\cf0\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 Vision of the hands and catching.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \u8194\'20}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 An important question related to catching is this: }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2
Must a person be able to see his or her hands throughout the flight of a ball to successfully catch the ball?}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2
 In one of the first experiments investigating this question, Smyth and Marriott (1982) attached a screen to the participants so they could see the oncoming ball, but not their hands. When the participants were able to see their hands, they averaged 17.5 catches out of 20 balls thrown. However, when they could }
{\f3\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 not}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  see their hands, they were able to catch an average of }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2
\line }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 9.2 balls out of 20. More important, when they could }{\f3\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 not}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2
 see their hands, participants typically made a hand-positioning error: }{\f5\fs20\b0\i0\expnd0\expndtw-2 T}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2
hey could not get their hands into the correct spatial position to intercept the ball. But when they could see their hands, their typical errors involved grasping: }
{\f5\fs20\b0\i0\expnd0\expndtw-2 T}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 hey initiated too early the finger flexion they needed to grasp the ball.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \par }\pard\plain \s12\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 Interesting as the Smyth and Marriott results may be, research since their work has shown that }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2
experience}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  is an important factor influencing a person\rquote s catching success when he or she cannot see his or her hands. We might expect this, as Davids (1988) argued, because the effective use of peripheral vision is a function of age and experience. Because we use peripheral vision to see our hands as we try to catch an oncoming object, it is logical to expect that our need to see our hands to catch a ball will depend on our age and experience.\par }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 Fischman and Schneider (1985) provided empirical evidence that supports the influence of experience. Using the same experimental procedures as those of Smyth and Marriott, they included participants who had at least five years}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 \rquote  experience in varsity baseball or softball. The results of this experiment (figure 7.5) showed that although the number of catches decreased when the experienced people could not see their hands, the type of error did not depend on whether or not the participants could see their hands. However, for the inexperienced ball catchers, more positioning errors than grasp errors occurred when they could not see their hands.\par }
\pard\plain \s12\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 Researchers now generally agree that both ball catching experience and skill level influence the need for a person to see his or her hands while }
{\fs20 catching a ball (see Bennett, Davids, & Craig, 1999). More-\u173 ?experienced and skilled catchers do not need to see their hands; less-experienced and low-skill catchers require vision of their hands. The reason for this difference appears to relate to a person\rquote s capability to use proprioceptive feedback to catch a moving object. The less-experienced, low-skilled person needs visual feedback to assist in the use of proprioceptive feedback to spatially position his or her arms and hands and to effectively grasp the object. In terms of helping people improve their catching skill, this relationship between experience and the need for vision of the hands suggests that beginners and less-skilled people should practice catching primarily in situations where they can see their hands throughout the ball flight, from the point where the ball leaves the thrower\rquote s hand until the ball is grasped.\par }
\pard\plain \s18\f4\fs21\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb350\sa120\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\keepn\caps\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs21 Striking a Moving Object}{\fs21 \par }\pard\plain \s11\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 Like the action of catching a moving object, striking a moving object involves the spatial and \u173 ?temporal interception of an object. And, as we \u173 ?
discussed for catching, the motor control of this \u173 ?action involves the coordination of movements that is influenced by vision in specific ways. Two experiments investigating the striking of a moving \u173 ?
object illustrate how vision influences the control of this action.\par }\pard\plain \s13\f4\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Vision and Baseball Batting}{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s11\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 The classic experiment related to the role of vision in baseball batting was performed many years ago by Hubbard and Seng (1954). Using cinematography techniques, they found that professional baseball players tracked the ball only to a point, at which time they made their swing. This point did not coincide with the point where the bat made contact with the ball. Each batter tended to synchronize the start of the step forward with the release of the ball from the pitcher\rquote s hand. And, perhaps most important, the durations of the batters\rquote  swings were remarkably consistent from swing to swing, indicating that it was the initiation of the swing that batters adjusted according to the speed of the oncoming pitch. Interestingly, these findings agree precisely with expectations from a }
{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw2 tau}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 -based strategy for \u173 ?hitting. That is, the initiation of the batting action occurred at a critical time to contact.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 \par }\pard\plain \s12\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 Some of the findings of Hubbard and Seng have been either verified or extended in research reported since their study. For example, thirty years later, Bahill and LaRitz (1984) used more sophisticated technology to closely monitor eye and head movements of a major league baseball player and several college baseball players. The study was done in a laboratory situation that simulated players\rquote  responses to a high-and-outside fastball thrown by a left-handed pitcher to a right-handed batter. The major league player visually tracked the ball longer than the college players did. The college players tracked the ball to a point about 9 ft in front of the plate, at which point their visual tracking began to fall behind the ball. The major league player kept up with the ball until it reached a point about 5.5 ft in front of the plate before falling behind in his tracking. Also, regardless of the pitch speed, the major league player followed the same visual tracking pattern and was very consistent in every stance he took to prepare for the pitch. While tracking the ball, his head position changed less than one degree across all pitches but he never moved \u173 ?
his\u8239 ?body.\par }{\fs20 Batting also involves perception-action coupling, as demonstrated in research by Katsumata (2008). Two timing characteristics showed this coupling. First, as other researchers have reported, the timing of the initiation of stepping with the front foot and its associated weight shift was influenced by the speed of the pitch; stepping initiation began later for slow pitches than for fast pitches. Second, the coordination of the timing of the initiation of the batter\rquote s moving his front foot forward and the initiation of swinging the bat was consistent regardless of pitch speed. Thus the temporal coupling of these events establishes a well-\line developed coordinative structure for the action of batting a pitched baseball.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1 \par }\pard\plain \s13\f4\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Vision and Table Tennis Striking}{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s11\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 In a study of five top table tennis players in the Netherlands, Bootsma and van Wieringen (1990, 2010) showed inconsistencies in the players\rquote  hitting movements because they were using online visual control. Players seemed to com\u173 ?
pensate for differences in the initiation times of their swings in order to hit the ball as fast and as \u173 ?accurately as possible. For example, when time to contact between the ball and paddle was shorter at swing initiation, players compensated by swinging more quickly. And evidence suggests that some of these players were making very fine adjustments to their swings while they were moving. Thus, whereas visual information may trigger the initiation of the swing and provide information about its essential characteristics, vision also provides online }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 feedback}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0  information that the player can use to make subtle compensatory adjustments to the initiated swing.\par }
\pard\plain \s18\f4\fs21\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb360\sa120\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\keepn\caps\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs21 Locomotion\par }\pard\plain \s11\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 There is general agreement that at the nervous system level, }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i central pattern generators}{\fs20  (CPGs) in the spinal cord are involved in the control of human locomotion, which you will sometimes see referred to as gait (see Zehr & Duysens, 2004; Rossignol, Dubuc, & Gossard, 2006, }
{\fs20 and Ziskind-Conhaim & Hochman, 2017,}{\fs20  for reviews of CPGs). These mechanisms provide the basis for stereotypic locomotive patterns such as walking and running. We can trace evidence for this spinal level of control to the work of the British Nobel laureate Sir Charles Sherrington and his colleagues at the end of the nineteenth and beginning of the twentieth centuries (e.g., Sherrington, 1906).}
{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s12\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 Using a procedure known as decerebration, which involves severing the brainstem and spinal cord from the forebrain, Sherrington observed that decerebrated cats performed locomotor rhythmic muscular activity similar to that performed by intact animals. Later, Brown (1911) went a step further by additionally severing a cat\rquote s sensory pathways to the spinal cord; still, the cat showed rhythmic leg contractions \u173 ?
appropriate for walking. More recent research (e.g., Grillner, 1981, 1985) has confirmed and extended these earlier observations (see Field-Fote, 2000, for an excellent overview of the spinal cord\rquote s role in the control of locomotion).\par }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 It is important to note that }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 CPG}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  is a term used to\u8239 ?
refer to a \ldblquote functional network, generating the rhythm and shaping the pattern}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \rdblquote  of motor neuron activity (Zehr & Duysens, 2004, p. 348). For locomotion, the assumption is that we have at least one CPG per leg located in the spinal cord. Although \u173 ?
research evidence supports a CPG-based control of human locomotion, there is also evidence that the CPG is not the sole basis for this control. Results from several studies have shown that proprioceptive feedback from muscle spindles and Golgi-tendon organs can influence locomotor movement patterns (see Zehr & Duysens, 2004, for an excellent review of this research, as well as clinical \u173 ?
implications). For example, Dietz, M}{\*\cs61\f8\fs20\b0\i0\expnd0\expndtw-2 \'9f}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 ller, and Colombo\u8239 ?
(2002) mechanically induced paraplegic and tetraplegic \u173 ?patients to produce stepping movements on a \u173 ?treadmill and found evidence from EMG recordings that afferent feedback from the hip joints was an important part of the locomotor activity. A different approach involved using the tendon vibration technique that was described in chapter 6, with healthy participants (Verschueren, Swinnen, Desloovere, & Duysens, 2003). The researchers showed that tendon vibration of specific leg muscles influenced EMG amplitude and muscle \u173 ?
activity onset times for muscles involved in the swing and stance phases of walking.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \par }\pard\plain \s13\f4\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 The Rhythmic Structure of Locomotion\par }\pard\plain \s11\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 To understand how humans control the wide range of gait they are capable of, we must consider \u173 ?higher-}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1
level }{\fs20 nervous system involvement, along with \u173 ?musculoskeletal dynamics and environmental \u173 ?interactions. The rhythmic structure of locomotor actions is an important characteristic that will serve to \u173 ?
illustrate the roles of these various factors.}{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s12\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 In the discussion in chapter 5 of the study by Shapiro et al. (1981), you saw that on the basis of an analysis of the four components of the Phillipson step cycle, walking and running each have a distinct rhythmic structure. In fact, this rhythmic character\u173 ?
istic is so common for walking and running gaits \u173 ?that\u8239 ?mathematical models have been developed to describe their structures. Those who have developed these models view the leg movements in walking and running gaits as operating similar to a pendulum (see Wagenaar & van Emmerik, 1994; and Donker et al., 2001, for discussions about these models).\par }
{\fs20 The rhythmic structure of gait patterns is not limited to leg movements. For example, when a person walks, distinct }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0
rhythmic relationships exist between the movement of the arms and that of the legs,}{\fs20  and the specific character of this }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 relationship relates to walking speed. Craik, Herman, \line }{\fs20 and Finley (1976) first demonstrated this relationship by providing \u173 ?
evidence that there are two arm-leg coordination patterns for walking: a 2:1 ratio (i.e., two arm swings to each leg stride) for very slow walking, and a 1:1 ratio for walking at speeds greater than 0.75 m/s (1.7 mi/hr, or 2.72 km/hr). Van Emmerik and \u173 ?
Wagenaar (1996) reported that additional research has established that the transition from the 2:1 to the 1:1 arm-leg relationship occurs within the walking speed range of 0.2 to 1.2 m/s (0.5 to 2.7 mi/hr, or 0.3 to 4.32 km/hr). In addition to the arm-leg relationship, the pelvis and thorax also demonstrate a rhythmic relationship during walking. At lower speeds, they move in phase with each other, but out of phase at higher walking speeds.\par What is the practical benefit of knowing about these various coordination characteristics of gait patterns? Van Emmerik and Wagenaar (1996) pre\u173 ?
sented an excellent argument, along with research evidence, to support their view that knowing about these characteristics and using them as assessment techniques allow us to identify coordination problems in the trunk and extremities, especially for \u173 ?
people with Parkinson\rquote s disease. For example, when\u8239 ?walking at preferred speeds, Parkinson\rquote s \u173 ?patients show pelvis and thorax phase relationships that are exactly opposite to those \u173 ?
described in the previous paragraph for healthy people.}{\fs20 \par }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 Another example of the clinical use of coordination characteristics of gait patterns was presented in a study of people who recently had experienced anterior cruciate ligament (ACL) replacement surgery (Kurz, Stergiou, Buzzi, & Georgoulis, 2005). The researchers calculated the relative phase (a coordination quantification technique that was discussed in chapter 2) for the foot-shank and shank-thigh leg segments. The results showed relative phase characteristics for the ACL-reconstructed knee that differed from the normal knee. These differences led the researchers to conclude that the analysis of the relative phase dynamics of the reconstructed knee would provide clinically important information for patient performance at various stages of rehabilitation.\par }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 Another application of understanding the rhythmic coordination characteristics of gait is the use of this understanding to develop training or therapy strategies practitioners can use to help people improve their gait. For example, results from an experiment reported by Ford, Wagenaar, and Newell (2007) showed that post-stroke patients improved several aspects of their gait following treadmill training, with a metronome set at specific rhythmic frequencies (which systematically increased and decreased while the treadmill was at a constant speed), and with instructions to move their arms and legs to the beat of the metronome. The improvements included gait cadence, stride length, arm-leg swing coordination, and the phase relationship of the pelvic-thoracic rotation. (For a review of research concerning post-stroke interventions and gait control, see Hollands, Pelton, Tyson, Hollands, & van Vliet, 2012.) }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-5 \par }\pard\plain \s13\f4\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Head Stability and Locomotion}{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s11\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 When a person engages in locomotor activity, a goal\u8239 ?of the motor control system is to }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2
maintain head stability.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  Researchers have demonstrated that head stability, as measured by the vertical orientation and minimal horizontal motion, is maintained during locomotor actions such as walking, walking in place, running in place, and hopping (for brief reviews of this research literature, see Cromwell, Newton, & Carlton, 2001; and Holt, Ratcliffe, & Jeng, 1999). In addition, researchers who have investigated the head stability characteristics of people walking at their preferred speed have found that the least amount of head movement in the vertical and anterior}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 -\u173 ?}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 posterior planes occurs at the preferred walking speed (e.g., Latt, Menz, Fung, & Lord, 2008).\par }
\pard\plain \s12\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 Why is head stability so important to maintain during locomotion? The answer relates to the role the head plays. When we consider that the head contains the complex of sensory and motor ner\u8209 ?
vous system components essential for us to navigate through an environment and maintain postural stability so that we don}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4
\rquote t fall, it becomes evident that head stability is important to maintain during locomotion. In \u173 ?addition, maintaining a stable head position during \u173 ?
locomotion optimizes the use of vision in actions in which vision of an object while running is essential for achieving the action goal. For example, a baseball or tennis player must visually track the flight of the ball while running in order to catch or hit it. \u173 ?
Finally, it is interesting in light of the importance of head stability during \u173 ?locomotion that researchers have found that children with cerebral palsy and adults with neurological impairment commonly adopt what could be considered \ldblquote atypical\rdblquote  \u173 ?
postural and gait characteristics as strategies to en\u8209 ?able them to maintain head stability while walking (e.g., Holt, Jeng, Ratcliffe, & Hamill, 1995; Holt, Ratcliffe, & Jeng, 1999).}
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 \par }\pard\plain \s13\f4\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb320\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Gait Transitions\par }\pard\plain \s11\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 Another important gait characteristic, which was briefly described in chapter 5, is the spontaneous change from a walking to a running gait (and \line vice versa) at certain speeds. Although these spontaneous gait transitions are common to all people, the speed at which transition occurs varies \u173 ?
among individuals. Some people continue to walk at higher speeds than others, whereas some people continue to run at lower speeds than others. In addition, the walk-to-run transition typically occurs at higher speeds than the run-to-walk transition. (See DeSmet, Segers, Lenoir, & DeClercq, 2009, for a more indepth discussion about the kinematic characteristics of the walk-to-run transition, and for differences found for the transition on a treadmill compared to overground.)}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 \par }\pard\plain \s17\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb300\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs59\f6\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd0\expndtw-1\cf0\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 Why do spontaneous gait transitions occur?}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 \u8194\'20Rese\u173 ?archers have developed and tested several hypotheses to explain gait transitions (see Guerin & Bardy, 2008, for an overview of these hypotheses). The most prevalent of these has been that the transition occurs to minimize metabolic energy consumption (i.e., VO}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\sub 2}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 ). Although researchers have provided \u173 ?evidence that supports this hypothesis, \u173 ?
others have reported results that fail to support it (see Hreljac, 1993). At present, no single cause for gait transitions has been determined. Interestingly, Turvey et}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\u8239 ?al. (1999) expressed doubts that a single cause can be identified because of the nature of complex biological systems. Kao and Ringenbach (2004) found \u173 ?
evidence that supported the Turvey et al. conclusion by demonstrating that multiple factors, which may be specific to individuals, underlie gait transitions. }
{\f5\fs20\b0\i0\expnd0\expndtw-1 (For an excellent review of determinants of gait transitions see Kung et al., 2018.)}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1
\par }\pard\plain \s13\f4\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb420\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Vision and Locomotion}{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s11\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 In the preceding section, you saw that the control of locomotion depends on both proprioception and \u173 ?vision as sources of sensory information to augment and modify movement commands generated by the CNS. In this section we will look more specifically at the important roles that vision plays in two types of activities involving locomotion. As you will see, vision is more than a source of feedback; it also influences movement characteristics }
{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0 before}{\fs20  action initiation.\par }\pard\plain \s17\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb244\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 Contacting objects.\u8194\'20When you walk or run in your daily or sports activities, there are situations in which you must make contact with an object with one or both feet. For example, if you need to cross a street with a lot of puddles it is essential that your feet make contact with the dry areas among the puddles as you walk. In sports activities, baseball players must step on bases as they run, gymnasts performing the vault must contact the spring board with their feet at the end of the run-up, and long jumpers must step on the take-off board at the end of the run-up to the jumping area. \par }
\pard\plain \s12\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1 To discuss the motor control issues associated with making contact with objects with our feet during locomotor activity, we will use the long-jump situation as an example. It is an activity that many researchers have studied, with results that apply to other types of activities. To successfully perform the long jump, the athlete needs to make contact with the take-off board at maximum running speed. This run-up portion of the long jump can be thought of as similar to an aiming task; it requires the athlete to move a certain distance and then hit a target. The target is the take-off board, which is about 20 cm long (from front to back) and 1.2 m wide (from side to side). If any part of the athlete}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1 \rquote s foot extends beyond the back edge of the board (i.e., the edge nearer the landing pit), a foul is called and the jump does not count. On the other hand, if the tip of the foot strikes short of the\u8239 ?
board, the jump is that amount shorter because the\u8239 ?jump distance is measured from the back edge of the board.\par }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw2
The motor control question}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2  related to the run-up is this: What does the athlete do during the run-up to hit the take-off board as accurately as possible? One possibility is that the athlete performs the same \u173 ?
pro\u173 ?grammed step pattern during each run-up on each jump. This would mean that any error in hitting the take-off board would be due to an error in the programmed step pattern. However, research evidence has shown that this is }
{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw2 not}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2  what the athlete does. \u173 ?Although each long jumper takes a number of steps during each run-up that is specific to him or her, the step lengths of the last few steps vary across run-ups. Most scholars now agree that the reason for this is that the athletes use visual information that specifies the amount of time it will take to contact the take-off board. The motor control system uses this }
{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw2 time-to-contact}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2  information, which is specified by the visual variable }
{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw2 tau}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2  (}{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw4\u964 ?}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 ), to make stride-length adjustments during the last few steps to correct for the targeting error that has accumulated during the run-up. Without these adjustments, the athlete would \u173 ?
either be short or long of the take-\line off board.\par }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 In what has become a classic experiment demonstrating this time-to-contact influence for a locomotor}
{\fs20  skill requiring object contact, Lee, Lishman, and Thomson (1982) filmed three highly skilled female long jumpers during their approaches to the take-off board. By analyzing stride-length changes as each athlete approached and contacted the \u173 ?
take-off board for a series of six long jumps, the researchers observed several \u173 ?important gait pattern characteristics. We will \u173 ?
examine these using the results from one of these \u173 ?athletes (an Olympic-level performer), presented in figure 7.7.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1
\par }{\fs20 Initially, the athlete\rquote s stride length increased at a }{\fs20 relatively constant rate for the first five to six strides; it then became similar for the next six strides. These strides were relatively consistent across the six jumps. Then, }
{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0 on the final six strides,}{\fs20  something different occurred. The athlete made stride-length adjustments so that she could hit the board accurately. In fact, she made almost 50 percent of these adjustments on the last stride. The lower half of the figure shows why she had to make these adjustments. As the athlete ran down the track, small inconsistencies in each stride had a cumu\u173 ?
lative effect, so that when she was five strides from the board the error had risen to 37 cm. If she had not adjusted her stride lengths on the remaining strides, she would have missed hitting the take-off board by a long distance.\par }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 These stride-length characteristics led the \u173 ?authors to describe the long jump run-up as consisting of two\u8239 ?
phases: an }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-1 initial accelerative phase,}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  where an athlete produces stereotypic stride patterns, followed by a }
{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-1 zeroing-in phase,}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  where the athlete modifies stride patterns to eliminate accumulated error. They concluded that a long jumper bases the correction process during the second phase on visual information obtained }
{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-1 in advance of}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  these strides. This means that the \u173 ?visual system picks up time-to-contact information from the board and directs the locomotor control system to make appropriate stride-length modifications for the strides remaining until contact with the take-off board.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 \par }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-5 It is worth noting that the use of visual time-to-\u173 ?contact information to regulate gait does}
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4  not \u173 ?depend on the expertise of the person. Although the participants in the Lee and authors long jump study were\u8239 ?
highly skilled, novice long jumpers also have demonstrated similar stride-length adjustments consistent with the influence of }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-5
tau}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4  (Berg, Wade, &\u8239 ?Greer, 1994).}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 \par }{\fs20 In the second phase of the run-up, the percentage of the total stride-length corrections made on each stride can be used as a way to demonstrate the }
{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0 perception-action coupling}{\fs20  involved in the long jump run-up. If }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0
tau}{\fs20  is the visual variable that influences the long jumper\rquote s performance during this phase of the run-up, we would expect to see \u173 ?
evidence of a coupling between the visually detected time-to-contact and movement corrections. This coupling would be best demonstrated by a linear relationship between the percentage of the total adjustment and the number of strides remaining to hit the take-off board. Montagne \line et al. (2000) presented evidence of this relationship in a study involving long jumpers of various levels of expertise. As you can see in }
{\fs20 figure\u8239 ?7.8, the per\u173 ?centage of the total amount of adjustment increased linearly for the final five strides from the take-off board. And, similar to what Lee, Lishman, and Thomson (1982) found for elite jumpers, approximately 40\u8239 ?
per\u173 ?cent of the total amount \u173 ?of\u8239 ?adjustment occurred on the stride before the \u173 ?take-off board.}{\fs20 \par Researchers have found that other types of gait also involve adjustments during locomotion on the basis of visual time-to-contact information. Some examples are walking a given distance and stepping on the target with a specified foot (Laurent \line & Thomson, 1988); running and stepping on targets, as people do when crossing a creek on rocks \u173 ?
(Warren, Young, & Lee, 1986); doing run-ups to the\u8239 ?springboard and horse while performing the vault in women\rquote s gymnastics (Meeuwsen }
{\fs20 & Magill, 1987). In all of these activities, the persons adjust stride length on the basis of time-to-contact information as they near the targets.\par }
\pard\plain \s17\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 Avoiding contact with objects.\u8194\'20When you walk through a doorway, you want to avoid contact with the sides of the doorway. How do you successfully achieve the action goal of this locomotor activity? Research evidence indicates that vision provides the motor system with }
{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i body-scaled information}{\fs20  about the size of a specific body part in relation to the size of the doorway. A person decides how to orient his or her body to walk through an open doorway on the basis of \u173 ?
visually perceived information related to the proportion of his or her shoulder width to the width of the door opening. More specifically, Warren and Whang }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 (1987) reported that a doorway needs to be 1.3 times }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 wider than the person\rquote s shoulder width for the person}
{\fs20  to determine that he or she can walk through it without having to turn his or her shoulders.\par }\pard\plain \s12\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 A different type of object avoidance situation \u173 ?occurs when we need to go safely over an obstacle in our pathway. People can employ a variety of avoidance strategies while walking or running to accomplish this goal. Patla and his colleagues reported several studies in which they investigated the role \u173 ?
vision plays in the strategy people select to go over an\u8239 ?obstacle (e.g., \u173 ?Mohagheghi, Moraes, }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2
& Patla, 2004}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 ; }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 Patla et al., 2002). Here again, vision provides predictive information that specifies to the motor control system the type of step-pattern }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2\u173 ?}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 alteration that will be needed to step over the object. The primary information is specified by the height, width, and shape of the object. In addition, predictions about how solid or fragile the object is are also important. For example, people will increase the height of their leading leg, which increases the amount of toe clearance, more for an obstacle perceived to be fragile than for an object perceived to be solid.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 And, in a study by Matthis, Yates, and Mayhoe (2018), walkers in a variety of outdoor natural terrains, from smooth to very rugged, demonstrated precise coordination between the biomechanics of their gait and eye movements that gathered the information the walkers needed to guide their foot placements. The walkers maintained a constant }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \ldblquote }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 look-ahead}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \rdblquote }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2
 gaze across all terrains.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \par }\pard\plain \s19\f4\fs18\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li120\ri0\sb0\sa250\facenter\sl220\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\caps\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs18 Summary\par }\pard\plain \s20\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 Much of our understanding of the control processes underlying the performance of motor skills comes from research evidence that has identified specific performance characteristics associated with a variety of types of skills. This discussion highlighted several of these characteristics.\par }
\pard\plain \s21\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi-170\li170\ri0\sb120\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i Speed-accuracy skills,}{\fs20  which require a person to produce movement that is both fast and accurate, typically demonstrate a speed-accuracy trade-off. That is, if the movement must be as accurate as possible, people move at a slower rate of speed than when accuracy is not important. Fitts\rquote  law provides a mathematical basis for predicting this trade-off on the basis of the task\rquote s movement \u173 ?
distance and target size characteristics.}{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s22\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi-200\li370\ri0\sb60\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 Fitts\rquote  law applies to a wide range of motor skill performance situations in daily living \u173 ?activities and sports skills.}
{\fs20 \par Both open- and closed-loop motor control processes operate when a person performs a speed-accuracy skill.\par }\pard\plain \s23\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi-200\li370\ri0\sb60\sa60\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 The role of vision in the control of speed-\u173 ?accuracy skills depends on the phase of the limb movement.}{\fs20 \par }
\pard\plain \s21\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi-170\li170\ri0\sb120\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 Performance of }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i prehension skills,}{\fs20  which involve the reaching for and grasping of objects, demonstrates the synergistic temporal coupling of movement components that allow a person to achieve an action goal in a variety of situations. The transport and grasp components function \u173 ?
interdependently by adjusting certain movement kinematics to adapt to specific characteristics of the object to be grasped and the manipulation goal of the prehensive action. Unlike manual aiming, pointing, and reaching, prehension movement kinematics vary during both the transport and the grasp phases as a function of what the performer intends to do with the object after it is grasped.\par }
\pard\plain \s22\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi-200\li370\ri0\sb60\sa60\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 The role of vision in the control of prehension skills is similar to that of speed-accuracy skills except that visual feedback influences the grasp component according to the grasp and object manipulation requirements of the intended use of the object.}
{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s21\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi-170\li170\ri0\sb120\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd1\expndtw4 Handwriting}{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw4  demonstrates an important motor control characteristic known as motor equivalence, which means that a person can achieve the same action goal in a variety of situations that require movement adaptations dictated by the environmental context or by task characteristics such as size, force, direction, and \u173 ?
muscles involved. The movement adaptations \u173 ?result in \u173 ?remarkable similarities in handwriting characteristics such as letter forms and the \u173 ?
relative time \u173 ?relationship between strokes, among \u173 ?others.\par }\pard\plain \s22\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi-200\li370\ri0\sb60\sa60\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 Vision influences the control of the overall spatial arrangement of words on a horizontal line and the production of accurate handwriting patterns.\par }
\pard\plain \s21\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi-170\li170\ri0\sb70\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i Bimanual coordination skills}{\fs20  require the simul\u173 ?taneous performance of the two arms. Some tasks\u8239 ?
require symmetric bimanual coordination (i.e.,\u8239 ?both arms perform in the same way at the same time); others require asymmetric bimanual \u173 ?
coordination (i.e., each arm performs differently). An important motor control characteristic of these skills is the natural, or intrinsic, spatial and temporal coupling of the arms, which means that we have a preference to move the arms symmetrically. Personal experience and research evidence shows that people can learn to uncouple the arms to perform asymmetric bimanual coordination skills. At the present time, researchers have not determined the specific motor control mechanism that underlies the control of arms in this \u173 ?
uncoupled, asymmetric state, especially in terms of the roles played by proprioceptive and visual feedback.\par }\pard\plain \s21\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi-170\li170\ri0\sb100\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 The }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i catching of moving objects}{\fs20  involves control processes similar to those for prehension actions except that catching involves intercepting a moving object and the grasping of the object ends the action. Catching involves three distinct movement phases: moving the arm and hand toward the oncoming object, shaping the hand to catch the object, and using the fingers and hand to }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 grasp the object. The first two phases are typically}{\fs20  completed by the time 75 percent of the object flight is complete.}
{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s22\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi-200\li370\ri0\sb60\sa60\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 Vision plays an important part in the control of catching by providing advance information to the CNS to enable the spatial and temporal presetting of the arms, hands, and fingers \u173 ?
before object arrival. Both central and peripheral vision operate in distinct ways to enable \u173 ?a\u8239 ?person to catch an oncoming object.\par }
\pard\plain \s23\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi-200\li370\ri0\sb60\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 Several factors related to vision influence the achievement of the action goal of catching a moving object. These include the amount of time of visual contact with the object, the portion of the object\rquote s flight during which visual contact occurs, and whether or not the hands can be seen during the object\rquote s flight.}
{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s21\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi-170\li170\ri0\sb120\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 The involvement of vision in the control of striking a moving object relates to the influence of \u173 ?vision on the initiation of the striking movements and the compensatory adjustments to the initiated movements.\par }
\pard\plain \s21\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi-170\li170\ri0\sb100\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 The performance of locomotion actions, such as walking and running, is characterized by the }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 rhythmic relationships that exist between stepcycle components, arm and leg movements, and the movement of the pelvis and thorax. Also, the maintenance of head stability is an important characteristic associated with locomotor activities. And a locomotion characteristic that has yet to be explained in terms of why it occurs is that spontaneous gait transitions (from walking to running, and running to walking) occur at certain gait speeds.\par }
\pard\plain \s22\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi-200\li370\ri0\sb60\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 At the nervous system level, central pattern generators (CPGs) in the spinal cord provide the basis for the stereotypic locomotor movement patterns, although proprioceptive and visual feedback are also important for the control of locomotion.\par }
\pard\plain \s22\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi-200\li370\ri0\sb44\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 The rhythmic structure of locomotion can be observed for the temporal relationships between the two legs as well as between the legs and arms.\par }
\pard\plain \s23\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi-200\li370\ri0\sb44\sa60\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 The importance and role of vision in the control of locomotion are especially notable in locomotor activities that require the feet to contact an object after running a certain distance (e.g., long jumping in track and field) and during walking or running (e.g., ascending and descending stairs) and the avoidance of contact with objects (e.g., walking in a crowded hallway).\par }
\pard\plain \s24\f4\fs18\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li120\ri0\sb0\sa100\facenter\sl220\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\caps\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs18 Points for the Practitioner\par }\pard\plain \s25\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi-170\li170\ri0\sb120\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 When helping people initially learn speed-\u173 ?accuracy}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  }{\fs20 skills, you should emphasize achieving the accuracy goal more than the speed goal.\par }
\pard\plain \s25\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi-170\li170\ri0\sb130\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 The application of Fitts\rquote  law to practice or training contexts, especially in terms of the index of difficulty (ID), can provide a basis for creating easier and more difficult variations of a skill for people to practice.}
{\fs20 \par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 When helping people rehabilitate their prehension capabilities, provide functional prehension activities that include a wide range of object sizes, reach distances, grip configurations, and object uses.\par }
{\fs20 When helping people learn or rehabilitate their handwriting skill, emphasize that they need to look at what they are writing; monitor this aspect of handwriting performance for evaluation and correction purposes.}
{\fs20 \par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 When helping people learn or rehabilitate the performance of bimanual coordination skills, give special attention to the difficulty people may have with learning asymmetric bimanual coordination skills.\par }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 When helping people learn or rehabilitate skills involving the interception of moving objects, such as catching and striking balls or other objects, emphasize the need to maintain visual contact with the object for as long as possible before it begins its flight and during its flight.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 \par }{\fs20 When helping people learn or rehabilitate locomotor actions, monitor the rhythmic relationship between the arms and legs and include this aspect of gait performance for evaluation and correction purposes.\par When helping people learn or rehabilitate locomotor actions, emphasize the need to maintain head stability during locomotion; monitor head movement during locomotion to evaluate head stability in terms of vertical orientation and the amount of horizontal motion of the head.}
{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s25\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi-170\li170\ri0\sb150\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 When helping people learn or rehabilitate locomotor actions, emphasize the need to maintain visual contact with an object that the person needs to step on or avoid contact with during locomotion; monitor this aspect of locomotion activity performance for evaluation and correction purposes.\par }
