{\fs19 Using Movement Therapy to Improve Prehension and Other Upper Extremity Skills \line for Individuals with Hemiparesis\par }
\pard\plain \s38\f5\fs18\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl220\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2 People with hemiparesis (i.e., partial paralysis on one side of the body) have difficulty using one arm, usually due to a stroke or other CNS disorder such as cerebral palsy. }
{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2 Two}{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2  physical rehabilitation intervention }{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2 strategies}{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2
 that }{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2 have}{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2  been shown to be effective as a treatment of upper-limb impairment for individuals with hemiparesis }
{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2 are}{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2  called }{\*\cs56\fs18\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 constraint-induced movement therapy}
{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2  (CIMT) }{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2 and }{\*\cs56\fs18\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 hand-arm bimanual intensive therapy}
{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2  (HABIT).}{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2  The goal of }{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2 both}{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2  }{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2
intervention therapies}{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2  is to encourage the use of the impaired arm to perform tasks that the impaired arm should perform}
{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2  alone or together with the other arm}{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2 . It is common for people with hemiparesis to eventually not use the impaired arm at all, a condition known as learned disuse. \par }
\pard\plain \s43\f5\fs18\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl220\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs18 The }{\fs18 CIMT}{\fs18  therapy, which was first introduced by Edward Taub and colleagues (see Taub, Crago, & Uswatte, 1998, for a review of the research and theory on which CIMT is based), involves \u173 ?
constraining the unimpaired arm with a splint, cast, or sling and forcing the use of the impaired arm. The\u8239 ?majority of the evidence supporting the efficacy\u8239 ?
of this treatment has come from patients with stroke, although more recent applications have been reported for children with cerebral palsy (CP) (see Gordon, Charles, & Wolf, 2005, for a brief review of this research).}
{\fs18 \par }\pard\plain \s44\f5\fs18\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb110\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl220\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2 The general protocol of CIMT:\u8194\'20The therapy is an intensive procedure that requires the active participation of the patient and therapists for several hours a day for two weeks. Patients typically have their unimpaired hand restrained for 90 percent of their waking hours for fourteen consecutive days, during which they engage in six hours of intensive repetitive task practice and \ldblquote shaping.\rdblquote  Tasks include screwing and unscrewing bolts, picking up coins and moving them to specified locations, and so on. }
{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2 \ldblquote Shaping\rdblquote  refers to practicing small parts of functional tasks and progressively increasing the complexity and difficulty of the parts until the actual functional task can be performed.\par }
{\fs18\expnd-1\expndtw-3 Effectiveness of CIMT:}{\*\cs66\f6\fs18\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd-1\expndtw-3\cf0\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0
\u8194\'20}{\fs18\expnd-1\expndtw-3 Numerous research studies have provided results that describe the effectiveness of CIMT, especially for improving and increasing the daily functional use of the impaired arm. (For a review of the history of the development of CIMT and research that has demonstrated its effectiveness, see }
{\f5\fs18\b0\i0\expnd-1\expndtw-3 Fritz, Butts, & Wolf, 2012}{\fs18\expnd-1\expndtw-3 .)\par }\pard\plain \s43\f5\fs18\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl220\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2 The HABIT therapy was first introduced by Andrew Gordon and colleagues (see Gordon, Schneider, Chinnan, & Charles, 2007, for a discussion of a randomized control trial of the therapy with children with hemiplegic cerebral palsy). It also involves intensive activity with the impaired arm performing bimanual tasks with the unimpaired arm.\par }
\pard\plain \s44\f5\fs18\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb110\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl220\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2 The general protocol of HABIT:}{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2 \u8194\'20}{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2 The intensive procedure followed by this therapy involves the use of both arms to engage in play and functional activities, which include both fine and manipulative gross motor skills, for 10 out of 12 days in a two-week period. A }
{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2 \ldblquote }{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2 shaping}{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2 \rdblquote }{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2  approach, similar to CIMT, is also included.\par }
{\fs18\expnd-1\expndtw-4 Effectiveness of HABIT:}{\fs18\expnd-1\expndtw-4 \u8194\'20}{\fs18\expnd-1\expndtw-4 The original randomized control trial study reported by Gordon et al. (2007) found improvements in hand-use assessments, and increased use of impaired arm and hand use, and overall bimanual hand use. Reviews of research since that report have provided support for the efficacy of the HABIT therapy (e.g., Klepper, Krasinski, Gilb, & Khalil, 2017).}
