{\fs19 Relating Fitts\rquote  Law to Drinking from a Mug\par }\pard\plain \s38\f5\fs18\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl220\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2 In the experiment by Latash and Jaric (2002) the researchers studied }{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2 how people}
{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2  grasp, pick up, and sip from a mug, just as }{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2 they}{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2  would do in everyday life. As part of this study, they developed a way to identify the index of difficulty (ID) that accounted for mug size and the amount of liquid in the mug. Instead of target size and distance, the accuracy characteristic of most tasks researchers have used to investigate Fitts\rquote  law, they considered the accuracy component of the task to be the transporting of the mug from a tabletop to the mouth without spilling its contents. Their logic was that a mug that is full to its rim requires more movement accuracy and is therefore a more difficult task than a mug that is less full. And, if consistent with Fitts\rquote  law, this task should require more movement time than transporting the mug that is less full.\par }
\pard\plain \s44\f5\fs18\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb220\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl220\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs66\f6\fs18\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd-1\expndtw-4\cf0\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 Calculating the index of difficulty (ID):\u8194\'20}
{\fs18\expnd-1\expndtw-4 Four mugs of different diameters (3.2, 6.5, 8.5, and 10.0 cm) were filled with }{\fs18\expnd-1\expndtw-4
6 or 7 }{\fs18\expnd-1\expndtw-4 levels of water beginning from 0.5 to 1.0 cm from the rim to a small amount on the bottom. The researchers calculated the ID for each mug size and water level by determining the ratio of mug diameter to the distance of the water level from the mug rim\'d1that is, }
{\f3\fs18\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-4 mug diameter/water level distance \u173 ?(in\u8239 ?cm) from the rim}{\fs18\expnd-1\expndtw-4 . For example, the mug with a diameter of 10 cm that was filled with water to 1 cm from the rim had an ID of 10 (i.e., 10/1 }
{\*\cs58\f5\fs18\b0\i0\expnd-1\expndtw-4 =}{\fs18\expnd-1\expndtw-4  10); the same mug filled to 6 cm from the rim had an ID of 1.67 (i.e., 10/6 }
{\*\cs58\f5\fs18\b0\i0\expnd-1\expndtw-4 =}{\fs18\expnd-1\expndtw-4  1.67). The four mug sizes and water levels resulted in 16 IDs.}
{\fs18\expnd-1\expndtw-4 \par }{\*\cs66\f6\fs18\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd0\expndtw-1\cf0\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0
The relationship between ID and movement time }{\*\cs66\f6\fs18\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd0\expndtw-2\cf0\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0
(MT):\u8194\'20}{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2 When the participants\rquote  movement times (MTs) \line }{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-1 (f}{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw0
rom initial mug movement to initial mouth-mug contact) were compared for the 16 IDs, the results were consistent with the Fitts\rquote  law prediction that movement times would be fastest for the lowest IDs and slowest for the highest IDs.}
{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw0 \par }{\*\cs66\f6\fs18\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0
Relating the results to the control of the coordination of many degrees of freedom:\u8194\'20}{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw0 On the basis of the relationship between ID and MT, as well as other movement-related measures (head angle, mug tilt angle, and head position), the researchers concluded that \ldblquote ID could be viewed as a significant parameter that reflects task constraints within the natural movement of taking a sip from a mug}
{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw0 \rdblquote  (p. 147). In terms of\u8239 ?the nervous system\rquote s control of the coordination of hand, arm, and head movements required to perform this task (which represents the control of many degrees of freedom), this conclusion means that the ratio of the mug diameter to the distance of the contents from the rim directly influences the nervous system\rquote s spatial and temporal organization of the appropriate coordination elements to allow a person to drink from a mug without spilling its contents.}
