{\fs18 A common instruction coaches give when teaching hitting in baseball is to tell players, \ldblquote Watch the ball all the way to your bat.\rdblquote  In light of this, it is interesting to note that research (e.g., Bahill }
{\fs18 & LaRitz, 1984) indicates that batters probably never see the bat hit the ball. If they do, it is because they have jumped in their visual focus from some point in the ball flight to the bat contact point. They do not visually track the ball continuously all the way to bat contact because this is virtually a physical impossibility. Batters commonly track the ball to a certain point and then visually jump to a point where they predict the ball will be at bat contact.\par }
\pard\plain \s43\f5\fs18\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl220\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs18 It is worth noting that more-skilled batters watch the ball for a longer amount of time than less-skilled players. Beginners tend to have the bat swing initiation movement influence their head position and \ldblquote pull\rdblquote  their head out of position to see the ball/bat contact area.\par }
{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2 From an instruction point of view, these characteristics suggest that }{\*\cs56\fs18\b0\i it is worthwhile}
