{\fs19 Visual Cues Can Aid Walking for People with Parkinson\rquote s Disease\par }\pard\plain \s38\f5\fs18\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl220\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs18 One of the primary movement disorders common to people who have Parkinson\rquote s disease is slowness of gait (i.e., gait hypokinesia). Two questions have interested researchers and physical therapists concerning this gait problem. One, what movement characteristic accounts for the slowness? Two possibilities are \u173 ?
cadence, which would mean that the difficulty relates to the rhythm, or beat, of the walking pace, and stride length, which would mean that the slowness is due to strides that are shorter than normal. The answer to this question is important for the second question: Is there a rehabilitation strategy that would help patients improve their control of walking gait speed?\par }
\pard\plain \s43\f5\fs18\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl220\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2 To address these questions, Morris, Iansek, Matyas, \line and Summers (1994) compared walking gaits of }
{\fs18\expnd1\expndtw3 Parkinson}{\fs18\expnd1\expndtw3 \rquote s patients with age-matched controls (60}{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2
\'d085\u8239 ?years old) for instructions to walk along a 12-m walkway at \ldblquote a comfortable pace\rdblquote  and at a \ldblquote fast speed.\rdblquote  \line }
{\*\cs56\fs18\b0\i The results showed this:}{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2 \par }\pard\plain \s39\f5\fs18\ltrpar\ql\fi-155\li155\ri0\sb0\sa0\facenter\sl220\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs56\fs18\b0\i The Parkinson}{\*\cs56\fs18\b0\i \rquote s patients walked more slowly than the control participants at both speeds, and had shorter stride lengths, but similar cadences.}
{\fs18 \par }\pard\plain \s52\f5\fs18\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl220\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs18 Then, the researchers provided visual cues to the Parkinson\rquote s patients by placing 50 cm by 5 cm laminated strips of cardboard on the walkway at intervals matching the mean stride lengths of the control participants for each speed. The patients were instructed to walk over each floor marker as they walked along the walkway. }
{\*\cs56\fs18\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0 The results showed this:}{\fs18 \par }\pard\plain \s39\f5\fs18\ltrpar\ql\fi-155\li155\ri0\sb0\sa0\facenter\sl220\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs56\fs18\b0\i The patients\rquote  velocity and stride lengths were similar to the controls for both speeds.}{\fs18 \par }\pard\plain \s38\f5\fs18\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl220\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs18 The researchers concluded from their results that the regulation of stride length was the \ldblquote key deficit\rdblquote  in gait slowness for patients with Parkinson}
{\fs18 \rquote s disease. And visual cues can be an effective rehabilitation strategy for helping these patients regulate gait speed.\par }
\pard\plain \s43\f5\fs18\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl220\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2 Evidence that the improvement in these gait characteristics can be long-lasting was provided in a case study reported by Sidaway, Anderson, Danielson, Martin, and Smith (2006). The Parkinson\rquote s patient walked during a four-week training period with visual cues on the floor that were similar to those used in the Morris et al. (1994) experiment. At the end of the training period, the patient\rquote s stride length and gait speed improved. What was especially impressive, however, was that these improvements were maintained without the use of the visual cues one month after the training ended. }
{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2 More recent evidence of the visual-cueing benefit was presented by Vitorio et al. (2014). Also, for an extensive review of research on this issue, which showed a large amount of evidence to support the visual-cueing benefit, see Rocha et al. (2014).}
{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2 \par }{\fs18\expnd-1\expndtw-4 In light of these results for visual cues, it is interesting to note that several researchers (e.g., Baker, Rochester, & Nieuwboer, 2007; McIntosh, Brown, Rice, & Thaut, 1997}
